1
00:00:09,560 --> 00:00:11,520
(ROARING)

2
00:00:11,600 --> 00:00:13,080
(BELL TOLLING)

3
00:00:16,720 --> 00:00:17,920
(ROARS)

4
00:00:23,520 --> 00:00:25,360
OFFICER: Come on, out of the way.

5
00:00:25,440 --> 00:00:27,280
-Move yourself, please. Coming through.
-(SCREAMING)

6
00:00:27,360 --> 00:00:28,920
-There!
-That's it, excuse me, sir.

7
00:00:30,280 --> 00:00:32,240
(ALL CLAMOURING)

8
00:00:37,560 --> 00:00:40,280
Madame Vastra, thank God.

9
00:00:40,360 --> 00:00:42,280
I'll wager you've not seen anything
like this before!

10
00:00:42,600 --> 00:00:44,240
Well...

11
00:00:45,760 --> 00:00:47,400
not since I was a little girl.

12
00:00:47,680 --> 00:00:51,160
-JENNY: Big fellow, isn't he?
-Dinosaurs were mostly this size.

13
00:00:51,480 --> 00:00:53,760
I do believe it's a "she".

14
00:00:54,560 --> 00:00:57,880
-No, they weren't, I've seen fossils.
-I was there.

15
00:00:57,960 --> 00:00:59,080
Well, that's all well and good

16
00:00:59,160 --> 00:01:02,920
but what's this dinosaur fellow
doing in the Thames?

17
00:01:03,880 --> 00:01:06,360
It must have time-travelled. Jenny?

18
00:01:09,200 --> 00:01:10,720
Time-travelled?

19
00:01:11,720 --> 00:01:12,720
(WOMAN SCREAMS)

20
00:01:13,720 --> 00:01:14,800
Is it choking?

21
00:01:15,160 --> 00:01:17,280
There seems to be something
lodged in its throat.

22
00:01:17,400 --> 00:01:19,120
Well, how could it time-travel?

23
00:01:19,440 --> 00:01:22,200
I don't know.
Perhaps it was something it ate.

24
00:01:30,480 --> 00:01:31,480
(CROWD EXCLAIMING)

25
00:01:33,200 --> 00:01:35,960
Stand back. Stand back, stand back.

26
00:01:37,840 --> 00:01:40,040
Well, it's just laid an egg.

27
00:01:40,200 --> 00:01:44,200
It dropped a blue box marked
"Police" out of its mouth.

28
00:01:44,280 --> 00:01:46,960
Your grasp of biology troubles me.

29
00:01:49,400 --> 00:01:51,840
-It's the Tardis.
-It would seem so.

30
00:01:52,760 --> 00:01:54,280
We'll take care of this, Inspector.

31
00:01:54,360 --> 00:01:56,520
But what if that thing
goes on the rampage?

32
00:01:57,720 --> 00:02:00,240
Place these lanterns
on the shore line and bridges,

33
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:02,760
-encircling the creature...
-(DEVICE BEEPING)

34
00:02:02,840 --> 00:02:04,520
...twenty foot intervals.

35
00:02:04,640 --> 00:02:05,880
What will they do?

36
00:02:06,680 --> 00:02:08,600
They will emit a signal
that will incline it

37
00:02:08,680 --> 00:02:10,560
to remain within their circumference.

38
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:15,320
Jenny, Strax! With me.

39
00:02:17,480 --> 00:02:19,480
JENNY: So it's him, then? The Doctor.

40
00:02:19,600 --> 00:02:21,560
A giant dinosaur from the distant past

41
00:02:21,640 --> 00:02:25,840
has just vomited a blue box
from outer space.

42
00:02:26,760 --> 00:02:28,480
This is not a day for
jumping to conclusions.

43
00:02:28,600 --> 00:02:30,440
Stray, if you wouldn't mind?

44
00:02:39,360 --> 00:02:40,640
Hello?

45
00:02:40,720 --> 00:02:44,800
Exit the box and surrender to the glory
of the Sontaran Empire!

46
00:02:46,440 --> 00:02:47,960
Shush.

47
00:02:49,200 --> 00:02:50,240
Doctor?

48
00:02:52,520 --> 00:02:53,840
I was being chased by a giant dinosaur

49
00:02:53,920 --> 00:02:55,840
but I think I managed to
give it the slip.

50
00:03:11,440 --> 00:03:12,560
Sleepy?

51
00:03:12,680 --> 00:03:13,800
Sir?

52
00:03:16,200 --> 00:03:18,840
Bashful? Sneezy? Dopey?

53
00:03:21,520 --> 00:03:22,760
Grumpy!

54
00:03:25,880 --> 00:03:27,960
Oh, you two.

55
00:03:29,240 --> 00:03:32,640
The green one and the not-green one.

56
00:03:32,720 --> 00:03:35,400
Or it could be the other way round,
I mustn't pre-judge.

57
00:03:36,240 --> 00:03:37,440
Oh, you remember, uh...

58
00:03:43,640 --> 00:03:45,560
Thingy. The, uh...

59
00:03:46,320 --> 00:03:49,320
The not... The not-me one.
The asking-questions one.

60
00:03:49,640 --> 00:03:51,520
Names, not my area.

61
00:03:52,520 --> 00:03:53,640
Clara!

62
00:03:53,720 --> 00:03:56,240
It might be Clara, it might not be.
It's a lottery.

63
00:03:56,360 --> 00:03:58,240
-It is Clara.
-Well, I'm not ruling it out!

64
00:03:58,320 --> 00:03:59,640
- (DINOSAUR ROARING)
-Oi! Big man! Shut it!

65
00:04:02,400 --> 00:04:05,120
Oh! You've got a dinosaur, too!

66
00:04:07,960 --> 00:04:09,200
Big woman, sorry.

67
00:04:09,440 --> 00:04:12,920
Doctor, listen to me.
You... You need to calm down.

68
00:04:13,520 --> 00:04:17,080
-I'm not flirting, by the way.
-I think something's gone wrong.

69
00:04:19,240 --> 00:04:22,120
Wrong? What's gone wrong?

70
00:04:22,880 --> 00:04:24,040
Have you regenerated?

71
00:04:25,680 --> 00:04:27,080
I remember you!

72
00:04:28,320 --> 00:04:33,320
You're Handles! You used to be
a little...a little robot head

73
00:04:33,600 --> 00:04:37,040
and now you...
You've really let yourself go.

74
00:04:38,600 --> 00:04:40,480
(DINOSAUR ROARS)

75
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:44,400
Reduce the frequency.

76
00:04:45,480 --> 00:04:48,080
-I'm sorry?
-Your sonic lanterns, turn them down.

77
00:04:49,200 --> 00:04:51,560
-You're giving her a headache.
-Giving who a headache?

78
00:04:51,640 --> 00:04:54,320
My lady friend.

79
00:04:55,280 --> 00:04:56,480
Just an expression, don't get any ideas.

80
00:04:56,560 --> 00:04:57,640
But how do you know?

81
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,040
Come on, Clara!
You know that I speak dinosaur.

82
00:05:00,120 --> 00:05:02,040
He's not Clara. I'm Clara.

83
00:05:04,240 --> 00:05:05,480
Well, you're very similar heights.

84
00:05:06,080 --> 00:05:07,880
Maybe you should wear labels.

85
00:05:11,880 --> 00:05:12,880
Why...

86
00:05:13,360 --> 00:05:18,320
Why are you all doing that?
Why are you all going dark?

87
00:05:19,800 --> 00:05:22,600
-And wobbly, stop that.
-I don't think we are.

88
00:05:23,320 --> 00:05:26,800
Never mind! Everyone, take five.

89
00:05:34,280 --> 00:05:35,480
What do we do?

90
00:05:36,160 --> 00:05:39,880
I don't understand, who is he?
Where's the Doctor?

91
00:05:39,960 --> 00:05:43,800
Right here. That's him.

92
00:05:46,520 --> 00:05:47,840
That's the Doctor.

93
00:05:49,960 --> 00:05:51,520
Well, then. Here we go again.

94
00:06:02,520 --> 00:06:04,360
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

95
00:06:37,320 --> 00:06:38,600
(ROARING)

96
00:06:41,560 --> 00:06:44,080
DOCTOR:
It's simply misunderstand able to me.

97
00:06:44,160 --> 00:06:47,040
I don't know what it is.
Who invented this room?

98
00:06:47,640 --> 00:06:50,680
Doctor, please, you have to lie down.

99
00:06:50,760 --> 00:06:53,720
It doesn't make any sense.
Look, it's only got a bed in it.

100
00:06:53,800 --> 00:06:55,680
Why is there only a bed in it?

101
00:06:55,760 --> 00:06:58,680
Because it's a bedroom,
it's for sleeping in.

102
00:07:00,080 --> 00:07:03,680
-Okay, what do you do when you're awake?
-You leave the room.

103
00:07:05,040 --> 00:07:07,560
So you've got a whole room
for not being awake in?

104
00:07:08,600 --> 00:07:10,600
But what's the point?
You're just missing the room!

105
00:07:10,680 --> 00:07:13,120
And don't look in that mirror,
it's absolutely furious.

106
00:07:13,200 --> 00:07:17,240
Doctor, please. You have to lie down,
you keep passing out.

107
00:07:17,640 --> 00:07:19,960
Well, off course I keep passing out,
there's all these beds!

108
00:07:20,040 --> 00:07:24,200
Why do you keep talking like that?
What's gone wrong with your accent?

109
00:07:24,280 --> 00:07:26,120
Nothing's gone wrong with her accent.

110
00:07:26,360 --> 00:07:28,360
You sound the same, it's spreading.

111
00:07:28,440 --> 00:07:31,800
You all sound all English,

112
00:07:31,880 --> 00:07:33,800
now you've all developed a fault!

113
00:07:34,120 --> 00:07:37,360
Doctor, I need your help with something.

114
00:07:37,880 --> 00:07:40,760
Finally, someone who can talk properly.

115
00:07:41,880 --> 00:07:43,880
I'm having difficulty sleeping.

116
00:07:43,960 --> 00:07:47,600
Oh? Oh, well, I wouldn't bother
with that, I never bother with sleep,

117
00:07:47,680 --> 00:07:48,960
I just do standy-up catnaps.

118
00:07:49,040 --> 00:07:53,000
Oh, really? How interesting.
And when do you do those?

119
00:07:53,080 --> 00:07:55,640
Well, generally whenever anyone else
starts talking.

120
00:07:55,720 --> 00:07:57,400
I like to skip ahead to my bits,
it saves time.

121
00:07:57,480 --> 00:08:00,560
Oh. Save me time, Doctor,

122
00:08:00,720 --> 00:08:05,960
project an image of perfect sleep
into the centre of my mind.

123
00:08:06,040 --> 00:08:07,640
What, you want a psychic link with me?

124
00:08:08,400 --> 00:08:10,560
The size of my brain, it would be like
dropping a piano on you.

125
00:08:11,920 --> 00:08:13,040
Be gentle, then.

126
00:08:13,800 --> 00:08:16,040
I'll try. Brace yourself.

127
00:08:17,800 --> 00:08:18,800
Piano.

128
00:08:22,080 --> 00:08:23,720
VASTRA: I love monkeys,
they're so funny!

129
00:08:23,800 --> 00:08:26,800
Oh, I see!
So people are monkeys now, are they?

130
00:08:27,120 --> 00:08:32,640
No, dear, people are apes.
Men are monkeys.

131
00:08:33,520 --> 00:08:36,200
-So what now?
-He needs rest.

132
00:08:36,280 --> 00:08:38,040
-So what do we do? How do we fix him?
-Fix him?

133
00:08:38,120 --> 00:08:40,400
How do we change him back?

134
00:08:42,200 --> 00:08:45,240
Jenny, I will be in my chamber.

135
00:08:45,320 --> 00:08:47,120
Would you be kind enough
to fetch my veil?

136
00:08:47,480 --> 00:08:49,440
Why? Are we expecting strangers?

137
00:08:50,280 --> 00:08:54,320
It would seem there is already one here.

138
00:09:00,640 --> 00:09:02,520
What have I done wrong?

139
00:09:02,600 --> 00:09:04,240
(DINOSAUR STOMPING AND ROARING)

140
00:09:04,320 --> 00:09:08,160
-The dinosaur doesn't seem very happy.
-What's wrong with it?

141
00:09:08,240 --> 00:09:09,240
I don't know.

142
00:09:10,040 --> 00:09:12,480
The Doctor's the one
that speaks dinosaur.

143
00:09:15,840 --> 00:09:19,320
Excuse me, ma'am, the wife
doesn't like to be kept waiting.

144
00:09:21,400 --> 00:09:23,520
Where did he get that face?

145
00:09:24,040 --> 00:09:26,360
Why has it got lines on it?
It's brand-new.

146
00:09:26,800 --> 00:09:30,280
How can his hair be all grey?
He only just got it.

147
00:09:31,120 --> 00:09:34,280
It's still him, ma'am,
you saw him change.

148
00:09:35,840 --> 00:09:38,760
-I know. I do. I... I know that.
-Good.

149
00:09:38,840 --> 00:09:40,440
-It's just...
-What?

150
00:09:40,520 --> 00:09:41,560
Nothing.

151
00:09:43,120 --> 00:09:47,600
If... If Vastra changed,
if she was different,

152
00:09:47,680 --> 00:09:51,000
if she wasn't
the person that you liked?

153
00:09:53,600 --> 00:09:56,840
I don't like her, ma'am, I love her.

154
00:09:58,800 --> 00:10:02,120
And as to different,
well, she's a lizard.

155
00:10:12,960 --> 00:10:14,720
(DINOSAUR MOANING)

156
00:10:26,800 --> 00:10:27,800
(DINOSAUR MOANING)

157
00:10:31,800 --> 00:10:33,000
I am alone.

158
00:10:34,840 --> 00:10:39,320
The world which shook at my feet

159
00:10:40,360 --> 00:10:42,400
and the trees

160
00:10:43,280 --> 00:10:46,880
and the sky have gone

161
00:10:49,760 --> 00:10:51,200
and I am alone now...

162
00:10:53,080 --> 00:10:54,080
Alone.

163
00:10:55,640 --> 00:10:56,880
Are you translating?

164
00:10:57,640 --> 00:11:00,000
The wind bites now

165
00:11:01,600 --> 00:11:04,280
and the world is grey

166
00:11:06,320 --> 00:11:08,800
and I am alone.

167
00:11:09,960 --> 00:11:13,960
Can't see me. Doesn't see me.

168
00:11:15,480 --> 00:11:18,040
Can't see me.

169
00:11:18,680 --> 00:11:21,160
You can't see it?
I think all of London can see it.

170
00:11:22,920 --> 00:11:25,440
STRAX: Boy? Madame Vastra is waiting.

171
00:11:27,560 --> 00:11:31,240
-Okay, whatever.
-I will convey you to her chamber.

172
00:11:32,040 --> 00:11:33,240
May I take your coat?

173
00:11:34,720 --> 00:11:37,120
-Not wearing a coat.
-What's all that?

174
00:11:37,200 --> 00:11:38,240
Clothes.

175
00:11:38,960 --> 00:11:41,520
-May I take your clothes?
-Probably not.

176
00:11:41,880 --> 00:11:44,120
-Are you wearing a hat?
-It's hair.

177
00:11:44,200 --> 00:11:46,040
No, I think it's a hat,
would you like me to check?

178
00:11:49,960 --> 00:11:53,920
(CROWD CHATTERING, DINOSAUR GROWLING)

179
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:59,320
MAN: It's not real, of course.
WOMAN: What is it, then?

180
00:11:59,760 --> 00:12:01,800
-The government.
-The government?

181
00:12:01,880 --> 00:12:03,880
Yeah, up to their usual tricks.

182
00:12:03,960 --> 00:12:07,240
It's a dinosaur, Alf. A real dinosaur.

183
00:12:07,320 --> 00:12:08,560
I wouldn't put it past them.

184
00:12:08,640 --> 00:12:10,760
You don't half talk
a lot of rubbish, Alfie.

185
00:12:11,680 --> 00:12:13,320
See you don't stay out too late, now.

186
00:12:13,560 --> 00:12:15,840
-You know me.
-Yes, I do.

187
00:12:27,040 --> 00:12:29,640
It's the neck,
that's what's wrong with it.

188
00:12:29,720 --> 00:12:30,960
It just don't look realistic.

189
00:12:31,960 --> 00:12:35,840
-You have good eyes.
-I do, as it happens. Very good eyes.

190
00:12:36,560 --> 00:12:37,680
They're my greatest gift.

191
00:12:39,280 --> 00:12:42,240
-I accept.
-What's that for?

192
00:12:42,880 --> 00:12:45,720
Your gift. I have bad eyes.

193
00:12:45,960 --> 00:12:46,960
(YELPS)

194
00:12:47,920 --> 00:12:49,040
And then?

195
00:12:51,400 --> 00:12:53,880
-Why are you wearing your veil?
-And then?

196
00:12:54,680 --> 00:12:59,360
And then we got swallowed by a big
dinosaur. You probably noticed.

197
00:13:00,160 --> 00:13:03,640
-How did it happen?
-I don't know. I don't know, we were...

198
00:13:05,120 --> 00:13:06,440
crashing about everywhere.

199
00:13:06,520 --> 00:13:08,440
The Doctor was gone,
the Tardis went haywire.

200
00:13:08,520 --> 00:13:10,920
He's not gone. He's upstairs.

201
00:13:14,760 --> 00:13:18,760
-Okay, he changed.
-He regenerated. Renewed himself.

202
00:13:18,840 --> 00:13:20,800
Renewed, fine.

203
00:13:22,120 --> 00:13:23,640
Such a cynical smile.

204
00:13:25,400 --> 00:13:26,560
I'm not smiling.

205
00:13:26,640 --> 00:13:30,560
Not outwardly. But I am accustomed
to seeing through a veil.

206
00:13:31,520 --> 00:13:33,040
How have I amused you?

207
00:13:33,760 --> 00:13:36,960
You said renewed. He doesn't...

208
00:13:37,040 --> 00:13:39,680
He doesn't look renewed, he looks older.

209
00:13:40,280 --> 00:13:42,680
-You thought he was young?
-He looked young.

210
00:13:43,560 --> 00:13:47,640
He looked like your dashing young
gentleman friend. Your lover, even.

211
00:13:48,120 --> 00:13:50,960
-Shut up!
-But he is the Doctor.

212
00:13:51,040 --> 00:13:54,240
He has walked this universe
for centuries untold,

213
00:13:54,320 --> 00:13:56,280
he has seen stars fall to dust.

214
00:13:56,800 --> 00:13:58,920
You might as well flirt
with a mountain range.

215
00:13:59,360 --> 00:14:02,440
-I did not flirt with him.
-He flirted with you.

216
00:14:04,440 --> 00:14:06,600
-How?
-He looked young.

217
00:14:06,680 --> 00:14:08,160
Who do you think that was for?

218
00:14:10,600 --> 00:14:12,720
-Me?
-Everyone.

219
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:17,640
I wear a veil as he wore a face,
for the same reason.

220
00:14:18,040 --> 00:14:19,120
What reason?

221
00:14:19,200 --> 00:14:21,280
The oldest reason there is for anything.

222
00:14:22,560 --> 00:14:24,440
To be accepted.

223
00:14:29,200 --> 00:14:30,200
(SNIFFING)

224
00:14:31,400 --> 00:14:33,120
(INHALES SHARPLY)

225
00:14:34,280 --> 00:14:35,680
(CONTINUES SNIFFING)

226
00:15:03,560 --> 00:15:07,240
Jenny and I are married,
yet for appearances' sake,

227
00:15:07,320 --> 00:15:10,800
we maintain a pretence in public
that she is my maid.

228
00:15:11,560 --> 00:15:15,200
Doesn't exactly explain
why I'm pouring tea in private.

229
00:15:15,280 --> 00:15:17,760
-Hush, now.
-Good pretence, isn't it?

230
00:15:18,600 --> 00:15:20,560
I wear a veil to keep from view

231
00:15:20,640 --> 00:15:24,080
what many are pleased to call
my disfigurement.

232
00:15:25,400 --> 00:15:28,040
I do not wear it
as a courtesy to such people

233
00:15:28,200 --> 00:15:32,440
but as a judgment
on the quality of their hearts.

234
00:15:33,680 --> 00:15:35,760
Are you judging me?

235
00:15:37,040 --> 00:15:39,960
The Doctor regenerated in your presence.

236
00:15:40,440 --> 00:15:42,760
The young man disappeared,
the veil lifted.

237
00:15:43,520 --> 00:15:47,000
He trusted you. Are you judging him?

238
00:15:47,400 --> 00:15:48,400
(SCOFFS)

239
00:15:55,160 --> 00:15:58,640
How dare you? How dare you?

240
00:16:03,560 --> 00:16:05,320
(DINOSAUR ROARING)

241
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:18,600
Door. Boring! Not me.

242
00:16:25,440 --> 00:16:26,720
Me!

243
00:16:27,400 --> 00:16:29,760
Marcus Aurelius, Roman Emperor,
last of the Five Good

244
00:16:29,840 --> 00:16:31,120
and stoic philosopher.

245
00:16:31,280 --> 00:16:34,480
Superlative bass guitarist. The Doctor
really knows how to put a band together.

246
00:16:34,560 --> 00:16:36,640
And the only pin-up I ever had
on my wall when I was 15,

247
00:16:36,720 --> 00:16:37,760
only one I ever had.

248
00:16:37,840 --> 00:16:40,480
I am not sure who you think you're
talking to right now, Madam Vastra,

249
00:16:40,560 --> 00:16:42,920
but I have never had the slightest
interest in pretty young men.

250
